26. quo animo: ablative of characteristic.

Legati . . . appellati superbius: this seems a very mild statement of the offense. The Roman ambassadors at Corinth, according to Polybius, attempted to address the meeting of the Aehaean League, but were insulted and driven from the assembly. The war which followed resulted in the destruction of Corinth and the complete conquest of Greece hythe Romans, in the year 146 nc. This war, however, is a good illustration of the eager· ness with which the Romans seized upon any and every pretext for extending the boundaries of their empire. .
